"{\n  \"text\": \"We live in a culture that is filled with autoimmune disorders and chronic inflammation. This is directly from your gut health. Your gut is basically an anaerobic or oxygen-free processing system. But the food we eat is covered in aerobic bacteria because we live in an oxygen-rich environment. Consequently, our gut bacteria has to fight this to neutralize it so that we can properly digest the sugar, starches, fats, proteins, and all the different things that our food offers us. But if our gut biome isn't doing a good job, this pathogenic bacteria leaks through the gut wall and into our circulatory system. And this is where the problems start, because our circulatory system is the is an immune system, our N2H2 immune system that's not designed for this. It's designed for basic maintenance construction, but it's not designed to fight this heavy bacteria that your gut was supposed to fight. And so when this happens, your body becomes tri your immune system becomes triggered and it basically creates inflammation throughout your system, and then we feed it this pathogenic bacteria constantly, day after day after day, and it builds up and it wears us down and eventually we're sick and we're sick in chronic ways. We're sick in a way where our body is making itself sick because we've constantly triggered our immune system. Gut health is so fundamental to our existence. And what we're doing as Americans is destroying our gut health because we don't eat enough raw and fermented foods. But also because of antibiotics and antibacterial soap, chlorinated water, and all the different things that are are killing our biomes. And basically, we've waged war against bacteria without realizing our fundamental processes are bacterial in nature. Anyway, that's why we need to do better with our guts, because we're never going to get well with an unhealthy gut. You can't be healthy with an unhealthy gut biome.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" We live in a 